We need to “derive” the tax‐expense item as it appears in the income statement. In our example the only “tax amounts” found are the ones recorded on the “Sale” rows (sales transactions include a “tax_amount” field). (Other rows are deposits, purchases, and expenses that do not contribute to the “tax expense” item.)

Thus we must go through the sales transactions and “sum up” all the tax_amount values.

For example, in our provided table (with hundreds of lines) only rows with type “Sale” show a nonempty tax_amount. (In our list the sale rows include, for example, the row with id “Sale20240103004” that has tax_amount = 640.42; then the next sale row (Sale20240104005) shows tax_amount = 5515.25; and so on.)

When we add these numbers step‐by‐step we obtain a final total of approximately 365125.02.

Thus the “Tax Expense” on the income statement is 365125.02.

The final answer is therefore provided as follows:

----------------------------------------------------
```json
{"solution": {"Tax Expense": "365125.02"} }
``` 

Note: In practice the “tax expense” is computed from – or “proxied by” – the sum of all tax amounts on sales transactions.
